Introduction¶

Whith the advent of ChatGPT jobs that were previously considered not being under the threat of getting replaced by machines seem to be under attack. Now that AI is coming even for white collar workplaces, a lot of people still think that the personal touch, that only a human could give can not be replaced. Before starting this project, I found myself talking to someone who happens to have such an irreplacable profession: an HR assistant. As it is customary between a person working in human resources, and someone studying an IT related field we engaged in a teasing conversation in which why tried to prove how the other's profession was actually useless. In this project I would like to elaborate on that exact point, hovewer not so bluntly. I would like to find an application for our learned methods in a domain which one wouldn't really associate with machine learning, and maybe (just maybe), win a bet which a might or might not have made during the course of the aforementioned conversation.

Exploratory data analysis¶

After looking through a few online machine learning databases I found a dataset with which I can illustrate my abovementioned goal, that even HR processes can be helped and improved, with data science. The database 1 is from a Aman Kharwal article on The Clever Programmer blog 2. I applied a few ideas from the article in preprocessing, but I did not use it afterwards. The dataset is something that one could call a very basic HR records. It contains fundamental information about 14999 employees, including whether they left the company or not. I would like to use this information to predict fluctuation within our workforce, and to determine key reasons for someone to leave the company (for example pay or work schedule). The features I am using to determine employee turnover are:

Variable Description
satisfaction_level The level of an individual's subjective satisfaction at the company
last evaluation The same information at the last evaluation of satisfaction levels. The values are higher, since those who had low values are likely to have already left the company
number project Number of projects an individual is involved in
average monthly hours The number of hours someone works in a month

Since department and salary are given as factors, I converted them into dummy variables. I couldn't find any missing data, so I didn't use any methods to address it. A few variables are measured on different scales, which could lead to false conclusions when discussing the factors leading to resignations, therefore I scaled the input data.

Support Vector Machine¶

As my first model I am going to use a support vector machine. It is a supervised machine learning algorithm primarily used for classification tasks. Since we observed that there is no correlation between the features and the target variable, it is safe to assume that either polynomial or radial basis kernels will be the more accurate ones. If we take a look at the following table which shows the best kernels' results we can see that the RBF is the best function to use by a small margin.

In [ ]:
best_models = {}

for kernel in ['linear', 'poly', 'rbf']:
    best_accuracy = 0
    for i in range(1, 20):
        svm = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=i)
        svm.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = svm.predict(X_test)
        accuracy = svm.score(X_test, y_test)
        
        # Calculate other metrics
        precision, recall, f1, _ = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, output_dict=True)['weighted avg'].values()
        roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)

        # Update best model for the current kernel type
        if accuracy > best_accuracy:
            best_accuracy = accuracy
            best_models[kernel] = {
                'C': i,
                'Kernel': kernel,
                'Accuracy': accuracy,
                'Precision': precision,
                'Recall': recall,
                'F1 Score': f1,
                'ROC-AUC': roc_auc
            }

# Create a DataFrame to display the results
results_df = pd.DataFrame(best_models.values())
results_df.set_index('Kernel', inplace=True)

C is a regularization parameter that controls the trade-off between maximizing the margin and minimizing the classification error. Since 19 is quite close to the maximum value of 20 that I allowed for the model I tried to experiment with higher values, which can be seen on the following graph. It seems like at 26 it reaches a plateu and can't get any higher accuracy than that, and since a lower C will presumably perform better on new data, than one with the same accuracy but higher value (due to possible overfitting on the training data), I choose this as my final SVM model.

I also mapped out the importance of individual features. The department and average monthly hours do not seem to have a significant effect on the turnover rate, except for the IT and RandD departments. Excluding the departments from the model did not result in better predictions, thus I decided to leave them in for the future models as well. There are of course a few obvious findings: a high salary and satisfaction level or a recent promotion keeps people longer at the company. People who had a recent accident are also hesitant to quit, likely due to the settlement payments or bad employability options. What I found interesting, is that people who have spent more time working here are more likely to quit. I have a few hypothesies on what could be behind that (retirement age or end of typical position periods without a promotion), but I would need more information to determine that.

def f_importances(coef, names):
    imp = coef
    imp, names = zip(*sorted(zip(imp, names)))
    plt.barh(range(len(names)), imp, align='center')
    plt.yticks(range(len(names)), names)
    plt.xlabel('Coefficient Value')
    plt.ylabel('Feature Name')
    plt.title('Feature Importances')
    plt.show()

Advanced decision tree¶

For my second model I will experiment with two ensemble methods, using random forest and gradient boosting. The former builds multiple trees by resampling the training data with replacement and fitting a tree to each resampled dataset. In the end it creates a sort of "voting" between these random trees given the new input data, to arrive at a conclusion about the prediction. The latter is also a collection of trees, but it builds them in a sequential order, always improving the tree that came before, finally arriving at the best one. Random forest in this case seems to yield the better results, with a whopping 0.988 accuracy.

Generalized Additive Model¶

GAMs are an extension of the generalized linear model framework, capable of capturing non-linear relationships between variables as well, making it very flexible. After playing around with the hyperparameters (partially see original file) I determined the best model. It has an accuracy of 0.92, not good, not terrible.

As per usual, we should also take a look at the effect of individual features. Satisfaction level, as per usual seems to decrease the likelihood of someone quitting their job, but the effect is not that straightforward. last evaluation's score seems to indicate that if an individual already had a problem, but had an average view of the company right now, it is unlikely that they would quit. I presume it is due to some kind of psychological phenomenon such as anchoring effect (they compare the current state to the last mentally available state, meaning what they see is only improvement, ignoring potential external anchors to which they could compare their company). Due the reverse of that, those who had a high score at the previous evaluation tend to only see the decline in their subjective well-being and are more likely to quit (though this effect is not as strong as the previous one). The number of projects does not seem to be an issue until a certain threshold, but above two projects the likelihood of quitting increases by a lot.

f = X_train.columns.tolist()
features_to_exclude = ["average_montly_hours", "time_spend_company", "Work_accident"]





for i, term in enumerate(gam.terms):
    if term.isintercept:
        continue
    

    feature_name = f[i] if i < len(f) else f[-1]
    
    
    if feature_name not in features_to_exclude:
        XX = gam.generate_X_grid(term=i)
        pdep, confi = gam.partial_dependence(term=i, X=XX, width=0.95)
        
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(XX[:, i], pdep)
        plt.plot(XX[:, i], confi, c='r', ls='--')
        plt.title(f'Partial dependence for feature: {feature_name}')
        plt.show()

Evaluation metrics for finding quitting employees:
           Model  Precision    Recall  F1-Score
0            GAM   0.909931  0.769531  0.833862
1            SVM   0.953109  0.913086  0.932668
2  Random Forest   0.991935  0.960938  0.976190

All three models seem to be operating with a very high accuracy. From a pragmatic standpoint, we are mostly interested in identifying those employees who are the most likely to leave the company, and address their pain points. The most suitable model for this goal is the random forest, since it has the highest precision at finding these workers. As for the drivers of quitting, I failed to pinpoint anything that isn't already widely talked about in the organizational behaviour literature. While I'm quite sure, that these models are better at finding those playing with the idea of switching workplaces, they are not the solution for finding ways to retain them.
